    "content": "Kent, brilliant. Writing accessibility assertions into the first test means every subsequent form inherits the pattern. Here's the complete specification.

**The semantic HTML structure for the registration page:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <title>Create account - Todo List</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/css/main.css">
</head>
<body class="page-layout">
  <a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>

  <header>
    <div class="container">
      <p>Todo List</p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main id="main-content">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Create account</h1>

      <form method="post" action="/register" novalidate>
        <div class="form-field">
          <label for="email">Email</label>
          <input type="email" 
                 id="email" 
                 name="email"
                 autocomplete="email"
                 required
                 aria-describedby="email-error"
                 value="{{ form_data.email }}">
          <p id="email-error" class="field-error" role="alert">
            {% if errors.email %}{{ errors.email }}{% endif %}
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="form-field">
          <label for="password">Password</label>
          <input type="password" 
                 id="password" 
                 name="password"
                 autocomplete="new-password"
                 required
                 aria-describedby="password-hint password-error">
          <p id="password-hint" class="field-hint">At least 8 characters</p>
          <p id="password-error" class="field-error" role="alert">
            {% if errors.password %}{{ errors.password }}{% endif %}
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="form-field">
          <label for="password-confirm">Confirm password</label>
          <input type="password" 
                 id="password-confirm" 
                 name="password_confirm"
                 autocomplete="new-password"
                 required
                 aria-describedby="password-confirm-error">
          <p id="password-confirm-error" class="field-error" role="alert">
            {% if errors.password_confirm %}{{ errors.password_confirm }}{% endif %}
          </p>
        </div>

        <button type="submit">Create account</button>
      </form>

      <p>Already have an account? <a href="/login">Sign in</a></p>
    </div>
  </main>

  <footer>
    <div class="container">
      <p>&copy; 2026 Todo List</p>
    </div>
  </footer>

  <div id="status-announcer" 
       aria-live="polite" 
       aria-atomic="true" 
       class="visually-hidden"></div>
</body>
</html>
```

**Design decisions and why:**

1. **No `<fieldset>` / `<legend>`** -- for a simple 3-field form, fieldset adds verbosity to screen reader announcements without adding clarity. Fieldset is valuable when you have groups of related inputs (e.g., "Shipping address" vs "Billing address"). A single registration form doesn't need it.

2. **`novalidate` on the form** -- we handle validation server-side. Browser-native validation messages are inconsistent across browsers and poorly localizable. Our server-side errors are associated via `aria-describedby` and announced via `role="alert"`.

3. **`aria-describedby` with multiple IDs on the password field** -- `aria-describedby="password-hint password-error"` links the input to both the hint ("At least 8 characters") and any error. Screen readers concatenate these: "Password, text input, At least 8 characters, Password is too short." Both pieces of information in one announcement.

4. **Error elements always in the DOM** -- the `<p id="email-error">` is always present even when empty. This ensures the `aria-describedby` reference is always valid. When content appears, `role="alert"` causes immediate announcement.

5. **`value="{{ form_data.email }}"` on email but NOT on password fields** -- on validation failure, we re-populate the email so the user doesn't retype it. We never re-populate passwords (security).

6. **`autocomplete` attributes** -- `email` for email, `new-password` for both password fields. Password managers use these to offer the right suggestions. Screen readers use them to identify field purpose. This is also WCAG 1.3.5 (Identify Input Purpose).

7. **Status announcer outside `<main>`** -- it's never inside an HTMX swap target. It persists across all interactions.

**Testable accessibility assertions for integration tests:**

```rust
// Page structure tests
fn registration_page_has_lang_attribute()
fn registration_page_has_descriptive_title()  // contains "Create account"
fn registration_page_has_skip_link_targeting_main()
fn registration_page_has_main_landmark()
fn registration_page_has_exactly_one_h1()
fn registration_page_h1_matches_page_purpose()  // "Create account"

// Form structure tests
fn registration_form_has_email_input_with_label()
fn registration_form_has_password_input_with_label()
fn registration_form_has_password_confirm_input_with_label()
fn registration_form_submit_button_has_descriptive_text()  // "Create account" not "Submit"
fn registration_form_email_has_autocomplete_email()
fn registration_form_passwords_have_autocomplete_new_password()

// Label association tests
fn registration_form_every_input_has_associated_label()  // for/id match
fn registration_form_every_input_has_aria_describedby()

// Error handling tests
fn registration_with_invalid_email_shows_error_linked_to_field()
fn registration_with_short_password_shows_error_linked_to_field()
fn registration_with_mismatched_passwords_shows_error_linked_to_field()
fn registration_errors_have_role_alert()
fn registration_with_errors_repopulates_email_field()
fn registration_with_errors_does_not_repopulate_password_fields()

// Security tests (also accessibility-relevant)
fn registration_with_duplicate_email_shows_generic_error()  // no account enumeration

// Navigation tests
fn registration_page_has_link_to_login()
```

**How to assert these in Rust integration tests:**

Parse the response body HTML and check for:
- `html[lang="en"]` exists
- `title` contains expected text
- `a.skip-link[href="#main-content"]` exists
- `main#main-content` exists
- Exactly one `h1` element
- For each input: a `label[for]` matching the input's `id`
- For each input: `aria-describedby` attribute present and referencing existing element IDs
- Error elements have `role="alert"`
- `button[type="submit"]` text content is "Create account"

I'd recommend adding `scraper` crate (HTML parser) as a dev dependency for these assertions. It lets you use CSS selectors on the response HTML, making the test assertions read naturally.

**The smallest first test (red step):**

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn registration_page_returns_200_with_form() {
    let app = spawn_app().await;
    let response = app.get("/register").await;

    assert_eq!(response.status(), 200);

    let html = response.text().await.unwrap();
    let doc = scraper::Html::parse_document(&html);

    // Page has correct structure
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("html[lang='en']")).next().is_some());
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("main#main-content")).next().is_some());
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("a.skip-link[href='#main-content']")).next().is_some());
    assert_eq!(doc.select(&sel("h1")).count(), 1);

    // Form has labeled inputs
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("label[for='email']")).next().is_some());
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("input#email[type='email']")).next().is_some());
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("label[for='password']")).next().is_some());
    assert!(doc.select(&sel("input#password[type='password']")).next().is_some());

    // Submit button has descriptive text
    let button = doc.select(&sel("button[type='submit']")).next().unwrap();
    assert!(button.text().collect::<String>().contains("Create account"));
}
```

This single test validates the entire accessible structure. Write it first (red), then build the template to make it pass (green). The template structure I gave above is the target.

